04475nam a22006375i 9780674271999DE-B159720220131112047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220131t20222006mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806742719997 a10.4159/97806742719992doi  a(DE-B1597)613868  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aE162 7aHIS0360202bisacsh04a303.48/30973090331 aDelbourgo, James, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut12aA Most Amazing Scene of Wonders :bElectricity and Enlightenment in Early America /cJames Delbourgo. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2022] 4cÂ©2006  a1 online resource (384 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tIntroduction: Seizing the Lightning -- t1 Atlantic Circuits -- t2 Lightning Rods and the Direction of Nature -- t3 Wonderful Recreations -- t4 Electrical Politics and Political Electricity -- t5 How to Handle an Electric Eel -- t6 Electrical Humanitarianism -- t7 Electricity as Common Sense -- tConclusion: What Is American Enlightenment? -- tNotes -- tIllustration Sources -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBenjamin Franklin's invention of the lightning rod is the founding fable of American science, but Franklin was only one of many early Americans fascinated by electricity. As a dramatically new physical experience, electricity amazed those who dared to tame the lightning and set it coursing through their own bodies. Thanks to its technological and medical utility, but also its surprising ability to defy rational experimental mastery, electricity was a powerful experience of enlightenment, at once social, intellectual, and spiritual. In this compelling book, James Delbourgo moves beyond Franklin to trace the path of electricity through early American culture, exploring how the relationship between human, natural, and divine powers was understood in the eighteenth century. By examining the lives and visions of natural philosophers, spectacular showmen, religious preachers, and medical therapists, he shows how electrical experiences of wonder, terror, and awe were connected to a broad array of cultural concerns that defined the American Enlightenment. The history of lightning rods, electrical demonstrations, electric eels, and medical electricity reveals how early American science, medicine, and technology were shaped by a culture of commercial performance, evangelical religion, and republican politics from mid-century to the early republic. The first book to situate early American experimental science in the context of a transatlantic public sphere, A Most Amazing Scene of Wonders offers a captivating view of the origins of American science and the cultural meaning of the American Enlightenment. In a story of shocks and sparks from New England to the Caribbean, Delbourgo brilliantly illuminates a revolutionary New World of wonder.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aElectricityxExperimentsxHistoryy18th century. 0aEnlightenmentzUnited States. 0aSciencexSocial aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy18th century. 0aSciencezUnited StatesxHistoryy18th century. 7aHISTORY / United States / Colonial Period (1600-1775).2bisacsh40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674271999423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674271999/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK